      {
        "paragraph_index": 1,
        "text": "### Chemistry Insight\n\nThe very low (negative) first pKa reflects the strong acidity of the first proton — oxalic acid is one of the strongest organic acids, owing to the electron-withdrawing effect of the adjacent carboxyl group. The second dissociation (pKa₂ ≈ 3.8) is much weaker because removing a proton from the already negatively charged hydrogen oxalate ion is less favorable. This large gap (~5 pKa units) between the two steps is characteristic of small dicarboxylic acids and makes oxalate an effective chelating ligand for many metal ions (it forms stable bidentate complexes with Ca²⁺, Fe³⁺, Al³⁺, and others).",
